"Sapan" is derived from Hinduism and comes from the word "Sapna."  Sapna is the Hindi word that means "dream."  Sapna is used both in everyday language and also to name female children.  Sapan, which has the same meaning, is used to name male children.

Interestingly, several other cultures have the word "Sapan" in their vocabulary.  Spain itself is derived from the Phoenician word Sapan, which means "hidden".  In that context, Sapan refers to the desire to hide precious items to prevent them from being plundered by outsiders.  Psalm 48:2 makes a reference to Mount Sapan, which is found in the Ugaritic tablets.  Some scholars believe this is similar to the Hebrew word şafon (or saphon), which means North.  And, finally (although there are likely to be numerous other entities), Sapan appears in Korean in the expression ipan-sapan, which means "do or die."